518
56:07.110 --> 56:13.110
And there's an example
in the textbook content for this lesson that you can
check out if you're interested.

519
56:13.110 --> 56:20.550
In short, we can always divide the systems into two separate collections, the ones that are measured
and the ones that aren't.

520
56:20.550 --> 56:29.040
And once we've done that, we fall back on the method
method that I've just described, and that's how measurements for multiple quantum systems work.

521
56:29.040 --> 56:35.430
And now finally, we move on to unitary
operations on multiple systems.

522
56:35.430 --> 56:41.070
Using the same basic idea that multiple systems can be viewed as single compound systems.

523
56:41.070 --> 56:49.230
We conclude what you see
written here on the screen, quantum operations on compound systems are represented by unitary matrices

524
56:49.230 --> 56:56.850
just like we have for single systems and specifically the rows and columns of those unitary matrices correspond to the Cartesian product

525
56:56.850 --> 57:03.630
of the classical state sets of whatever collection of
systems we're talking about.

526
57:03.630 --> 57:10.080
For example, if we have a system X
whose classical states are one, two, and three and Y is a Qubit,

527
57:10.080 --> 57:18.600
then the matrix that you see right here is an example of a unitary matrix that represents an
operation on the pair XY.

528
57:18.600 --> 57:28.020
The details of how we
order Cartesian products that we talked about before don't really matter for
the sake of this example, it's just a six by six matrix
that happens to be unitary.

529
57:28.020 --> 57:32.910
There's nothing special about it, although it is built out of a
couple of important matrices.

530
57:32.910 --> 57:41.250
The point is that you could
choose any six by six unitary matrix and it would represent
a unitary operation on XY.

531
57:41.250 --> 57:47.850
If we apply a collection of
unitary operations independently each on its own system, then the action of them all together

532
57:47.850 --> 57:52.920
on the compound system is
given by the tensor product.

533
57:52.920 --> 57:57.150
And here on the screen you can see a more precise
statement of that fact.

534
57:57.150 --> 58:04.020
If our unitary operations are described by the unitary matrices U1 through Un one for each of our systems,

535
58:04.020 --> 58:11.580
then the combined action
on the compound system is given by the tensor
product of U1 up to Un.

536
58:11.580 --> 58:19.080
Once again, similar to what we had in the probabilistic setting, an important example is that
we apply some unitary operation

537
58:19.080 --> 58:23.670
U to a system X and we do
nothing to some other system Y.

538
58:23.670 --> 58:28.710
The operation on XY that we get is U tensored with the identity matrix.

539
58:28.710 --> 58:32.070
The identity matrix
describes doing nothing to Y.

540
58:32.070 --> 58:40.200
Sometimes it's helpful to write explicitly that this identity matrix
corresponds to the system Y, just to make the formulas more clear.

541
58:40.200 --> 58:47.640
And one option is to
give the identity matrix a subscript like this that indicates the system that it acts upon.

542
58:47.640 --> 58:55.050
When it's clear enough, though we usually don't
bother with a subscript, but when things get more complicated, it can be very helpful.

543
58:55.050 --> 59:02.760
And we can also consider
the symmetric case where some unitary
operation V is applied to Y and nothing is done to X,

544
59:02.760 --> 59:08.910
and this time the resulting
unitary operation on XY, is represented by this
tensor product here.

545
59:08.910 --> 59:15.990
And once again, we can put a subscript on the
identity matrix if it helps.

546
59:15.990 --> 59:19.590
Here are a couple of specific examples.

547
59:19.590 --> 59:29.970
If X and Y are Qubits and we
perform a Hadamard operation on X and we do nothing to Y, we get the matrix that you see right here.

548
59:29.970 --> 59:37.770
If on the other hand, we perform the Hadamard operation on Y and we do nothing to X, the ordering of the tensor
product is reversed.

549
59:37.770 --> 59:41.910
And so we get the matrix
that you see right here.

550
59:41.910 --> 59:47.160
Not every unitary operation
on a compound system can be expressed as a tensor product.

551
59:47.160 --> 59:50.940
If we have a tensor product,
then we have independence.

552
59:50.940 --> 59:58.560
And there are some pretty
fundamental examples of operations that certainly
don't act independently on multiple systems.

553
59:58.560 --> 60:04.740
For example, if X and Y have
the same classical state set, which could be any
classical state set sigma,

554
60:04.740 --> 60:09.060
then we can think about the
swap operation on the pair XY.

555
60:09.060 --> 60:17.490
This operation doesn't change the ordering of the two systems, we still have X in the
left and Y on the right, but rather it represents
swapping the contents

556
60:17.490 --> 60:27.270
of the two systems. Here you can see that expressed
in the form of an equation where we have a tensor
product of two quantum states.

557
60:27.270 --> 60:31.860
Another way to write it is as
a matrix as we see right here.

558
60:31.860 --> 60:37.560
The way you can think
about this description is that it tells you what happens for standard basis vectors.

559
60:37.560 --> 60:43.830
And once we know what happens
for standard basis vectors, we know what happens for
arbitrary quantum states by linearity,

560
60:43.830 --> 60:47.490
which in fact is also true for
this expression right here.

561
60:47.490 --> 60:56.520
So this particular operation right here happens to be a deterministic operation as well as a unitary operation.

562
60:56.520 --> 61:02.970
If X and Y are Qubits, for instance, we get this matrix
representation right here.

563
61:02.970 --> 61:10.680
Here's an interesting connection
between the swap operation and the four Bell states, which are shown right
here for convenience.

564
61:10.680 --> 61:17.010
The swap operation leaves the
first three of them alone, but it puts a minus sign in
front of the Psi minus state,

